INSERT INTO `testimonials` (`id`, `custumer`, `photo`, `review`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(1, 'Dr. Whitney Miller', 'phot', 'We know that dog parents are always looking for the best ways to give their pets the care they need to keep them healthy.\r\n\r\nPet parents should create a schedule with their veterinarian and groomer. Most breeds need to be bathed every 4–8 weeks and groomed every 6–12 weeks.\r\n\r\nEven if your dog looks healthy, routine vet exams can help detect diseases before they become serious and allow for early intervention. Your vet will track your dog’s development and answer questions about their overall health.\r\n\r\nWith Vital Care, your dog gets the care they need from our knowledgeable store associates, Petco-certified groomers and veterinary partners.', NULL, NULL),
(2, '<h4>Chris M</h4>\r\n<p>Sr. Dog Trainer, AKC CGC Evaluator, Petco Mentor University</p>', 'storage/1630620433.png', '<p>In 2007, I decided to dedicate myself to train through positive methods. Through fun positive reinforcement, I will help you to focus your dog in every way that you could need. My goal for every dog is to have your walk be off leash rules, for our on leash world.</p>', NULL, '2021-09-03 05:00:17'),
(3, '<h4>Elizabeth P</h4>\r\n<p>Sr. Dog Trainer, AKC CGC Evaluator – CPDT-KA, CCFT, Petco Mentor University</p>', 'storage/1630620476.png', '<p>While working toward my CPDT-KA (Certified Professional Dog Trainer-Knowledge Assessed) and my CCFT (Certified Canine Fitness Trainer) certifications I\'ve fallen in love with helping pet parents succeed in teaching their dogs basic skills for problem solving and keeping everyone confident and healthy along the way.</p>', '2021-09-03 08:39:03', '2021-09-03 04:57:23'),
(4, '<h3>Dr. Alexandra Horowitz</h3><h3>\r\n</h3><h4>Sr. Research Fellow and Head of the Dog Cognition Lab at Barnard College, Columbia University.</h4>', 'storage/1630778596.png', '<p>“To train a dog using positive reinforcement is to respect their dignity and worth as more than a possession obtained for personal satisfaction. If you want to build bonds with dogs, you must always choose a relationship built on positive reinforcement over one predicated on punishment, shame, or fear.”</p>', '2021-09-05 05:30:49', '2021-09-05 01:59:20'),
(5, '<h3>Dr. Whitney Miller, DVM, MBA, DACVPM</h3>\r\n<p>Petco head of veterinary medicine, board-certified in veterinary preventive medicine.</p>', 'storage/1630778618.png', '<p>“Positive reinforcement training is key to building lifelong bonds with our pets on a foundation of love and trust. As a veterinarian, I always recommend rewards-based training to pet parents looking for the best ways to keep the entire family healthy and happy together for as long as possible.\"</p>', '2021-09-05 05:30:49', '2021-09-05 02:01:40'),
(6, '<h3>Dr. Whitney Miller, DVM, MBA, DACVPM</h3>\r\n<p>Petco head of veterinary medicine, board-certified in veterinary preventive medicine.</p>', 'storage/1630779265.png', '<p>\"Positive reinforcement training is not only the right thing to do for the dogs involved, but the most effective and rewarding educational platform for pet parents, too.\"</p>', '2021-09-05 05:35:46', '2021-09-05 02:11:35');
